why china should keep its dollar peg a historical perspective from japan siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display why china should keep its dollar peg a historical perspective from japan type scid working paper 322 author s ronald mckinnon published 05 1 07 region china download pdf abstract this paper establishes the monetary rationale for china to use its dollar peg as an anchor for its domestic price level thereby avoiding a zero interest liquidity trap as a prelude the author's own monetary approach to the nominal exchange rate and price level is contrasted with the emphasis many economists place on the need to change real exchange rates to correct trade imbalances the paper then compares the situations of china and japan and concludes that in the long run in both china and japan exchange rate stability against the dollar is needed to prevent unduly low interest rates and deflationary traps the author hypothesizes that if both china and japan successfully stabilize their dollar exchange rates the smaller asian economies likely will follow suit stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
